A3: SPL Library Checkouts

Introduction

For this assignment, I want to look at the most popular authors based on the Seattle Public Library Checkout data. Specifically, I will be comparing the five most checked-out authors for both physical books and digital alternatives over the past few years. I chose to examine physical books separate from ebooks and audiobooks because Im curious if the medium of books will affect which authors are most popular. This could raise interesting questions like if some authors works are better experienced through digital mediums. After that, I will break down the genres of each book the most popular authors wrote to see if there is any takeaway about the most popular genres in Seattle library users.

The library has 12735615 items that are missing an author or creator. Of those 6305732 are physical books, 4044 are ebooks, and 48 are audiobooks. The other 29297593 items are all credited with an author or creator. That is the data that this assignment will analyze. The most popular book overall among the three mediums is Educated: A Memoir, which was written by Tara Westover.

The Dataset

This dataset was collected and published by the Seattle Public Library. The dataset tracks all checkouts from the library, which includes books (of all kinds), music, discs (video and sound), and various other library resources. For each item, the dataset tracks: - the usage class of each item - the way it was checked out - the type of item it was - the month and year it was checked out - the amount of times it was checked out for the respective month and year - the name or title of the item - the ISBN (International Standard Book Number) if applicable - the items creator or author - the items subject or genre - the publisher - and the publication date (typically just the year) This data was generated from the librarys system tracking the movement of resources that were logged. This dataset began in April of 2005 and was last updated February 6, 2023. This dataset doesnt track any specific people so privacy isnt a concern. Instead, since this dataset is messy, the biggest ethical concerns while using it are likely related to copyright and proper credit, as many accomplished creators works could be buried under inefficient labeling. This dataset only tracks behavior logged in the Seattle Public Librarys system, and as such is somewhat limited in scope. This means the data cant be used to make assumptions about book popularity as a whole. There are a lot of items with missing values as well, which should be taken into consideration when analyzing the dataset.

First Trends Over Time Chart

This chart is a trends-over-time chart that looks at the five most popular authors in the Seattle Public Library Database based on book checkouts. These authors were selected by having the highest total all-time checkout counts, and they are compared using their checkout count for each year between 2005 and 2022. For this chart I only looked at physical book checkouts because I wanted to compare these results to other formats.

One thing I noticed from the charts results is that by far the most checked out authors are childrens book authors. The ones that dont specialize in books for children in the top five and ten book checkouts are mostly writers of short and accessible literature like comic artists or young adult novelists. Overall, the trend of checkout data since 2005 has been that checkout counts for all authors have gone up, but it is unclear whether this is due to more customers, increased supply of books for each author, higher reading rates, or something else entirely.

Second Trends Over Time Chart

Include a chart. Make sure to describe why you included the chart, and what patterns emerged

This chart is a trends-over-time chart that looks at the five most popular creators in the Seattle Public Library Database based on ebook and audiobook checkouts. These authors were selected by having the highest total all-time checkout counts, and they are compared using their checkout count for each year between 2005 and 2022. For this chart I explored ebook and audiobook creators, because I wanted to see if the different medium would affect author checkout rates.

One thing I noticed from the charts results is that they are wildly different to the popular authors for physical book checkouts. There were fewer childrens book authors, and far more classics and young adult novelists. It seems as a trend popular ebook and audiobook authors audiences skew older, but there is still a preference for accessible works from authors with high output rates. Overall, the trend of this checkout data is also that checkout counts for all authors have gone up over time, but it is still unclear whether this is due to more customers, increased supply of books for each author, higher reading rates, or something else entirely.

Stacked Bar Chart

This final chart is a stacked bar chart that compares the top creators of physical books to the top creators of ebooks and audiobooks. Since there is already data in the previous charts related to their checkout counts, I wanted to instead explore the amount of works each creator has in the library, as well as the popular genres among the creators.

This chart showed a major outlier in book amount from James Patterson, and that overall popular authors tended to have a large amount of works, but that it wasnt a requirement. As for genres, the data was very messy, and so the most popular genre was just the generic label of Fiction. There were a couple interesting genres in the top ten for these creators, which included African American Fiction, Law, and True Crime.

This chart is a very rough, as the data involved was very messy. These only look at each authors physical or ebook counts respectively, rather than everything they have in the library. The book count is an approximation as well, as the library database has a large amount of repeat entries. I mostly combined the repeats, but at the cost of lumping together a lot of book series into one entry. The genre information is also very rough, as many books had unique subjects exlusive to their creator or series. This chart also ignores books tagged with more than one genre.
